\section{Introduction}
% Six or seven paragraphs - focus on socio-hydrological modelling

% Part 1: Global context, introduction to the ideas behind "socio-hydrology" (human-water interactions)
The equitable provision of freshwater to support human livelihoods and well-being and facilitate socioeconomic development, while ensuring the continued function of ecosystems and environment ``is one of the grand environmental challenges of the twenty-first century'' \citep{poff_sustainable_2016}. The pressure on global water resources is intensifying as a result of population growth and demographic changes combined with climate change and an associated increase in climate variability \citep{}. Water management is broadly defined as a set of activities related to the ``storage, abstraction and redistribution'' of water from various sources to meet a wide range of human resource demands \citep{nazemi_inclusion_2015}. Such activities can induce substantial changes in the natural regime of hydrological systems \citep{montanari_panta_2013}. For example, ... At the same time, the spatial and temporal dynamics of water availability is an important boundary condition to human activities such as food and energy production \citep{}, urbanisation and the management of urban systems \citep{}, and... \citep{}. Achieving sustainable and resilient water systems requires a systems approach \citep{kasprzyk_defining_2018}. Systems engineering is an ``Interdisciplinary approach that considers multiple subsystems, with the aim to provide an output that meets the end-users needs (INCOSE, 2015; De Graaf et al, 2017). It focuses on defining stakeholders needs and required functionality (Halbe et al., 2014) early in the development cycle, and then proceeding with design synthesis and system validation while considering the complete problem (operation and long term planning).'' In water resources management, systems engineering theory has been deployed... \citep[e.g.][]{}. Recently, \citep{} proposed to use systems engineering theory to improve water management in coupled human-water systems.\\

% notes on Blair & Buytaert, 2016
The coupling of human-water systems entails that decisions that impact upon the hydrological system may have both positive and negative impacts on society \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. According to \citet{norgaard_sociosystem_1981,norgaard_coevolutionary_1984}, a co-evolutionary relationship describes the situation where two systems influence the way in which each develops over time through the feedbacks and interactions that exist between them. While the concepts which underlie socio-hydrology have existed in various guises for some decades \citep[e.g.][]{}, for various reasons such as the inherent complexity of coupled, co-evolutionary systems as well as inadequate means of dealing with the associated epistomological uncertainties, the feedbacks between human-water systems are not usually included in models which seek to make predictions or inform policy \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. The use of stylized models is useful in order to highlight data gaps (both in terms of temporal and spatial coverage of conventional variables, as well as variables which provide insight into the relationship between human-water systems but which have not previously been monitored) \citep{di_baldassarre_debates-perspectives_2015}. The quality of a model should be assessed against its ability to to reproduce ``the emergent properties of the behaviour of a system'' \citep{}. \\

Bottom-up approaches seek to develop system behaviour through the explicit representation of process in the physical and societal domain. On the other hand, top-down approaches examine the system outcomes and attempt to identify causal relationships which between variables in order to determine how a system responds to change \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. A common criticisim of top-down approaches is their inability to disaggregate system-level outcomes and provide information which is relevant to individuals \citep{}. Our main interest in the present study is to explore the effects of spatial heterogeneity of input parameters on farmer livelihood, and conversely to gain insight into the effect of human activities, particularly irrigation, on the hydrology of the basin. Agent-based modelling is a bottom-up approach to modelling human-water systems, ``in which the focus is on the behaviour and decision-making of individual agents within a system''. The agents themselves may be ``individuals, groups of individuals, or institutions'', but should necessarily be autonomous and self-contained. An agent-based model may also include different types of agent, for example to represent a decision-making hierarchy \citep{}. Agents may interact with each other and/or the environment in which they exist. \\

Integrated water resources management \citep[IWRM][]{} is an approach to water management which recognises the role of humans in the water cycle. Under this paradigm major advances have been made in the provision of water resources \citep{}. However, it has several key shortcomings... human activities treated as boundary conditions \citep{elshafei_prototype_2014}. Coupled human-water systems are complex systems involving the ``multiple interacting components, local connections and nonlinear relationships between the components'' \citep{troy_debates-perspectives_2015}.\\

Hydrological modelling is fundamental to the hydrological sciences \citep{buytaert_why_2008}. From a practical perspective, hydrological models provide a representation of the hydrology of a catchment or other geographical entity in order to forecast its response to future conditions or to simulate the behaviour of catchments where no output or state variables are measures \citep{beven_modelling_2001}. On a more fundamental basis, hydrological models represent hypotheses about aspects of system behaviour \citep{}. As such, the practice of hydrological modelling should be viewed as a learning process... \citep{hrachowitz_decade_2013}. Socio-hydrology is an emerging discipline within the hydrological sciences which recognizes the interdependencies between social and hydrological systems and seeks to understand the complex feedbacks and interactions which govern their co-evolution in time and space \citep{montanari_panta_2013,savenije_evolving_2014,sivapalan_time_2015,kuil_exploring_2018}. Numerical modelling has emerged as an important mode of inquiry to advance our understanding of socio-hydrological systems \citep{}.\\

Modelling is a basic method of inquiry in Earth system science (``...regarded as the second Copernican revolution \citep{schellnhuber_earth_1999}). Modelling, in a broad sense, is a synthesis approach which formalizes our current knowledge and understanding about the Earth system \citep{li_watershed_2018}. Numerical modelling consists of input parameters and equations which can be used to gain a quantitative understanding of the Earth system (refs). A watershed model may be thought of as a basin-scale Earth system model \citep{li_watershed_2018}. The purpose of such models is twofold. First, they provide insight into the watershed system; second, they are used operationally to facilitate integrated river basin management \citep{}. Development of watershed models initially focused on improving the representation of physical processes. More recently, models have been extended to represent human processes such as land use change and intensification, water management activities \citep{nazemi_inclusion_2015}. Models such as SWAT and global scale models (PCR-GLOBWB, Community Water Model, H08). However, these models typically include the various results of human activities (e.g. water use in different sectors, land use change) as boundary conditions to the model. In reality, however, the human system and water system are inherently interlinked. This realisation is the basis of the Panta-Rhei initiative of IAHS \citep{montanari_panta_2013}, which has given rise to the nascent discipline of socio-hydrology. Modelling human systems draws on a range of disciplines including land use change, sociology, (hydro-)economics \citep{li_watershed_2018}.\\

``Watershed science'' aims to ``understand complex watershed behaviours according to fundamental science''. At the same time, it aims to inform integrated river basin management through applied science \citep{li_watershed_2018}. A major challenge in the development of watershed system models is to represent the co-evolution of human-water systems \citep{reid_earth_2010}. To the extent that human processes are included in models of physical systems, the conventional approach has been to force models with the physical manifestation of socioeconomic change and their physical manifestations (e.g. changes in land use or water demand). In models of human processes, such as land use change, physical constraints (e.g. water availability) are treated as boundary conditions \citep{li_watershed_2018}. In both cases, therefore, the various states of the opposing system are treated as exogenous variables which do not co-evolve \citep{}. The majority of socio-hydrological models are stylized system dynamics models. A promising approach is to use agent-based models, but there remain several key challenges in the design and implementation of these models. Coupling of models (human, water) needs to be ``cohesive, sufficiently detailed, and computationally tractable'' \citep{li_watershed_2018}. Parameterisation of agent-based models is difficult and requires data which is not usually in the public domain \citep{}. Physical processes are typically modelled in spatially distributed frameworks in order to account for spatial heterogeneity of model parameters and forcing data. On the other hand, socioeconomic processes are spatially lumped, using political boundaries (national or sub-national) to define the model scope. Natural systems contain ``fast'' processes, whereas human processes are relatively ``slow''. Hence, there is a need to either ``socialize the pixel'' or ``pixelize society'' \citep{}. \\

Developing models of these systems is challenging for various reasons [...] Furthermore, it requires effective collaboration between diverse research communities in order to include the state of the art in terms of the knowledge and understanding of system components \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}, which is often difficult \citep{montanari_panta_2013}. Various modelling paradigms have been used to represent socio-hydrological systems \citep{}. See \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. System dynamics, agent-based and so on. While IWRM has several conceptual shortcomings..., the lack of integration between human and environmental systems enabled modellers to develop sophisticated tools with which to understand the response of the hydrological system to changes in boundary conditions, some of which were related to human activities. On the other hand, current socio-hydrology models mainly consist of of stylized relationships intended to develop hypotheses about the system and explore its behaviour under different scenarios of social and environmental change \citep{van_emmerik_socio-hydrologic_2014,di_baldassarre_debates-perspectives_2015,garcia_question_2016}. However, there is a need to incorporate more realistic models capable of providing insight into socio-hydrological systems rather than simply reinforcing what is already known \citep{troy_debates-perspectives_2015,loucks_debates-perspectives_2015,blair_socio-hydrological_2016}, as well as making predictions about the co-evolution of social and hydrological systems under future conditions [Discuss notable examples - e.g. Srinivasan et al., O'Keeffe et al.]. This will involve more complete models of human behaviour \citep{loucks_debates-perspectives_2015}, as well as more accurate models of hydrological systems \citep{gober_debates-perspectives_2015,mount_data-driven_2016}.\\

For the most part, socio-hydrological modelling has focused on the temporal dynamics of coupled human-water systems \citep{pande_progress_2017}, although there are some exceptions. Consider the effect of groundwater abstraction on the baseflow component of streamflow. Of course, it is possible to develop empirical or conceptual representations of complex hydrological processes, but these typically require calibration. In the example, a baseflow index or similar would be required \citep{mackay_lumped_2014}. Spatio-temporal variability gives rise to interesting... For example, consider the competition for canal water between upstream and downstream farmers. At the same time, understanding the dynamics of coupled systems is reliant on an accurate representation of the underlying hydrological processes, regardless of the modelling approach. Data scarce regions typically do not have long-term observational data from which to derive empirical relationships. Low dimensional socio-hydrological have proven adept at highlighting the aggregated response of a system to change, but they are unable to model the distribution of the response in the physical and social realms \citep{srinivasan_prediction_2016}. In agricultural catchments, spatial heterogeneity in access to resources is a major determinant of wellbeing \citep{}. For example, farmers situated near the headwaters of a canal system tend to have a more reliable water source for irrigation than those farmers at the tail \citep{}. Moreover, incorporating a spatially explicit modelling approach may lead to a better representation of the underlying hydrology \citep{}.\\

% From review of Mostert et al: ``Human-environment competition for water resources in the context of irrigated agriculture''
Agriculture covers around 40\% of the Earth's land surface and consumes around 85\% of it's freshwater resources \citep{}. As a result of extensive land use change and agricultural intensification to meet the world's growing food demand, agriculture has substantially altered the global hydrological and ecological cycle \citep{gordon_managing_2010}. At the same time, almost X\% of global population depends on agricultural activities for their livelihood \citep{}. Worldwide, Y\% of farms are classed as smallholder farms \citep{}, where the occupying family supplies most of the labour \citep{}. As a result, smallholders have a crucial role in global agriculture and food security \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. A growing demand for food, combined with dietary shifts towards foods which require more water than traditional staple foods \citep{molden_???_2007}, puts additional pressure on farmers \citep{de_fraiture_satisfying_2010}. Hence there is a pressing need to better understand the socio-hydrology of agricultural catchments; particularlty in developing regions where smallholder farms dominate \citep{elshafei_prototype_2014}. Competition for water resources between the environment and irrigated agriculture has been an area of particular interest in socio-hydrology \citep[e.g.][]{kandasamy_socio-hydrologic_2014,liu_conceptual_2015,van_emmerik_socio-hydrologic_2014}. Various approaches to socio-hydrological modelling have been presented. Physical processes are usually represented in a simple way. For example, several models have explored irrigation water use... Crop yield determines farm income. The most common approach is to use the equations set out in FAO Irrigation and Drainage Paper ??, which requires potential yield estimates. Groundwater is often represented using a one-dimensional conceptual model (i.e. ignoring lateral groundwater flow). More complex aspects of the system are modelled using empirical relationships \citep{}. Society is modelled in numerous ways... \citep{mostert_alternative_2018}. In order to simulate the magnitidue and direction of change in system state variables it is necessary to accurately capture the underlying hydrological processes, such as river discharge, groundwater dynamics and root zone hydrology \citep{}. In data scarce regions, where there is typically very little data about important state variables and boundary conditions, developing conceptual relationships to describe key hydrological processes is difficult. Process-based models, on the other hand, are designed to simulate key processes based on process understanding. Earth system models now include water management activities such as ``irrigation schemes, reservoir operations and groundwater pumping'' \citep{voisin_effects_2017}. There have also been attempts to integrate aspects of the hydrological system in Integrated Assessment Models; a class of model which simulates the macroeconomy \citep{}. \\

Understanding the imperatives which guide smallholders' decision making, as well as the range of options available to them, is important to facilitate the adoption of more sustainable farming practices \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. Identifying the various factors which influence the adoption of new technilogies has been the focus of much previous research \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. Conceptually, decision-making may be considered as a stepwise process. Analytical farmers formulate quantitative goals and use calculations to assess the likely consequences of the various options in order to select the optimal decision. On the other hand, intuitive farmers set intuitive goals, which are often directional in nature (e.g. an increase in yield), based on their experience, available reference points and other types of auxillary data \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. There are a range of theories about decision making, many of which are included in models of coupled human-environment systems \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. However, many models are based on expected utility, and hence assume that humans make rational decisions and are ``able to choose the optimal outcome considering all possible combinations based on perfect information \citep{koelher_???_2008}''. Howver, for various reasons humans do not make perfect decisions \citep{kuil_exploring_2018}. It is therefore essential to involve decision makers during model conceptualisation in order to identify the imperatives which guide their decision-making process and the range of options they have available. \\

Previous socio-hydrological research has examined smallholders. However, so far there have been few attempts to explore the interactions and feedbacks which exist between smallholders and catchment hydrology. 

