  Moreover, a lack of discourse between modellers and and field experimentalists means that that the current generation of hydrological models do not always reflect the advances in process understanding gained from field studies \citep{mcdonnell_moving_2007,clark_framework_2008}. Here, we develop an integrated modelling framework to explore the socio-ecohydrology of the Gandak river basin, a subbasin of the Ganges located in northern India. The framework has been developed using a ``bottom-up'' approach, whereby field-level observations have been used to inform a conceptual model. It consists of individual models representing surface water hydrology, groundwater dynamics, crop production and the population dynamics of two important species. The flow of information between the models is governed by a farmer behaviour model which simulates the water management decisions of farmers in response to various biophysical and socioeconomic state variables. We conduct a number of experiments to test our hypothesis that interactions between surface water and groundwater ... important control on environmental flows and the wellbeing of agrarian communities. We follow an approach which starts with the collection of primary data, involving farmer intexrviews, ..., conceptual model development... numerical modelling framework to answer specific research questions.\\

