Managing the water resources of the Indo-Gangetic Plain is a complex task because of the basin's unique scale as well as the complexity of its biophysical, institutional and socioeconomic characteristics. Land use in this highly fertile and densely populated region is dominated by agriculture \citep{shah_is_2009}. This has been the case for at least 2000 years; however, a step change in agricultural productivity since India's green revolution, initiated in the mid-1960s, combined with unmanaged and inefficient water abstraction for irrigation, has led to degradation of the quantity and quality of water resources. Currently, irrigation accounts for more than 85\% of total water use, with up to 55\% of the net irrigated area supplied from groundwater \citep{ref}. The agricultural sector continues to be an important part of India's economy, employing more than 60\% of its working population and contributing around 18\% of the country's gross domestic product \citep{ref} [...]. Meanwhile the Ganga and its tributaries provide important habitats for culturally important yet critically endangered species such as the Gharial crocodile and the Ganges river dolphin \citep{}, as well as supporting the livelihoods of inland fishing communities, which are among India's most marginalised \citep{nachiket?}. \\

Water management in the Indo-Gangetic Plain is complicated by local regulations and governance structures which impede cross-sectoral cooperation and promote competition for scarce water resources \citep{tiwari_issues_2015}. The basin's groundwater resources, a primary source of irrigation and rural water supply to millions, are developed and managed independently by multiple agencies \citep{}. The socioeconomic heterogeneity of the Indo-Gangetic Plain has important implications both for farmer livelihood and food and water security. In the western states of Punjab and Haryana, as well as western Uttar Pradesh, substantial government subsidies for electricity combined with perverse incentives to grow certain crops has led to unsustainable cropping practices and falling groundwater levels \citep{rodell_satellite-based_2009,macdonald_groundwater_2016}. Nevertheless, farmer's in this region tend to be more prosperous than their counterparts in the eastern states of Uttar Pradesh and Bihar, who typically rely on inefficient and comparatively expensive diesel pumps for groundwater abstraction \citep{shah_climate_2009}. As a result, the eastern part of the IGP has been characterised as one of ``low productivity but high potential'' \citep{shah_climate_2009}, and creating the conditions in which the groundwater resource can be accessed sustainably is seen as the key to alleviating rural poverty while meeting India's growing food demand. \\

The Gandak basin is a sub-basin of the Ganges river in northern India, and is representative of many water management issues in the Indo-Gangetic Plain. The Gandak river originates in the Nhubin Himal glacier in the Nepal Himalaya, entering India at Triveni near Valmiki Nagar in the Pashchim Champaran district of Bihar. A large barrage on the India-Nepal border diverts flow into two large canal systems to the east and west of the river, respectively. A third canal system, slightly upstream of the barrage, enters a smaller canal system which serves Nepal. The primary purpose of the canal system is to supply irrigation water to farmers within the command area of the two canal systems. Downstream of the barrage, the Gandak river provides a number of important ecosystem services. The river is an important habitat of two critically endangered, yet culturally important, riverine species: the Ganges River dolphin and the Gharial crocodile. Additionally, the river supports fishing communities, which are among India's most marginalised. \\

The basin is a region with one of the highest rural population densities in India.
% Smallholder agriculture dominates. ``A typical smallholder farm can be described as a household in which mainly the family labor is used and for which the farm provides a principal source of income'' \citep{cornish_???_1998,morton_impact_2007}. ``Such farmers are assumed to practice subsistence-oriented activities (Dercon, 2009) that are a mix of farming and labor sale, where the majority of labor is provided by the smallholder's household'' \citep{pande_sociohydrological_2016}. Stakeholder groups - water managers, fishing, agriculture, conservation. 
% NB cornish_???_1998 is cited in morton_impact_2007, but difficult to find

It receives rainfall from both south-west and north-east monsoons of between 1100-1500 mm/year. Soils are mainly derived from calcereous alluvial deposits \citep{mohindra_historical_1992}. The predominant water uses are for agriculture and fisheries; the rivers in this are support important populations of highly endangered and unique riverine species such as the Ganges river dolphin and the gharial crocodile. High agricultural productivity and fertile soils characterise the alluvial floodplain region \citep{singh_???_2001}.% , and smallholder farming depends strongly on seasonal flood pulses and unaltered flow regimes in these rivers \citep{junk_???_1989} and maintaining ecological flow regimes is thus crucial [...].
\\

The barrage and its canal system was constructed in ? to supply water to two irrigation command areas: the western branch canal supplies farmers in Nepal and Uttar Pradesh, and the eastern branch canal which supplies farmers in Bihar. Barrage operations substantially affect boundary conditions of the Gandak basin; the release of water into the river for ecological flows and ecosystem services has a trade-off with respect to release of water into the canals. Despite the canal supply, the number of tubewells in the districts within the command area has increased dramatically in recent decades, in line with much of the rest of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, while the irrigated area supplied by canals has gradually fallen (Figure X). Interviewed farmers suggested that a lack of maintenance of the canal network is likely to be an important driver of this pattern. While in the Gandak basin groundwater levels are stable, much of the rural area is not covered by a reliable electricity supply and hence farmers must rely on costly diesel pumps to abstract water for irrigation. Previous research in the Indo-Gangetic Plain \citep{} has shown that smallholder farmers in the region are yield maximisers, as opposed to profit maximisers. \\

