\section{Model development}

\subsection{Overview}
In translating our perceptual model to a conceptual model, we acknowledge that ``Socio-hydrological systems can never be modelled exhaustively, but it is important to include the most influential variables and processes (see Garcia et al. 2016)'' \citep{mostert_alternative_2018}. \citet{garcia_question_2016} argue that, given the complexity of socio-hydrological systems, it is advisable to clearly define the objectives, or the questions one wishes to ask, of the socio-hydrological model. This should promote parsimony and transparency in the modelling approach \citep{garcia_question_2016}. The collection of primary and secondary data is identified as a crucial first step to the development of socio-hydrological model. In particular, stakeholder engagement is an essential first step to help to identify variables of interest \citep{melsen_what_2018}. While quantitative data is valuable for model calibration and validation, qualitative data is useful in developing a conceptual model of the problem \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. At the outset, therefore, define a central question(s) to guide the model development. As \citet{melsen_what_2018} point out, water availability is one of several boundary conditions for society.\\

Systems engineering theory focuses on defining the needs of stakeholders needs and required functionality... Identification of shared state variables. 

Data availability is a frequent barrier to the development of models which are relevant to stakeholders \citep{srinivasan_prediction_2016}. This is particularly the case in data scarce regions. To overcome these challenges, the model development process was informed by several stakeholder meeting at the outset of the model development process. We identified four key stakeholders, comprising the barrage authorities, conservationists, fishing communities and farmers. Stakeholder meetings were conducted with all of these groups. \\

In particular, there has been a concerted effort to develop flexible modelling frameworks that facilitate the systematic development, evaluation and comparison of multiple model structures as hypotheses of catchment behaviour, and the inclusion of additional and alternative process representations as our perceptual understanding of the system improves. This approach recognises that each catchment is unique and that fixed model structures are incapable of handling natural variability in space and time \citep{beven_???_2000}. [...] In this way, modelling frameworks facilitate collaboration between different parts of the hydrological modelling community in order to advance the theoretical basis of hydrological models and address major research challenges \citep{archfield_accelerating_2015,clark_improving_2016}.\\
