\subsection{Irrigation module}

% \subsubsection{Surfacewater abstraction}
The reliability of the canal network is an important influence on farm-level water management \citep{okeeffe_including_2018}. In general, the reliability of the canal network is related to the distance from the canal head, with farmers near the head receiving a more reliable service, and farmers near the tail receiving an unreliable service \citep{}.\\

\begin{equation}
  I_{s} = max(I_{t}, Canal)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $I_{s}$ is irrigation supply from the canal system, $I_{t}$ is total irrigation demand and $Canal$ is the canal supply, averaged over the grid cell. 

% \subsubsection{Groundwater abstraction}
We assume that farmers seek to exploit the groundwater resource for irrigation when they do not have access to canal water or when the canal supply is insufficient to meet demand. Hence, the demand for groundwater is computed:

\begin{equation}
  I_{g} = I_{total} - I_{s}
\end{equation}

The maximum quantity of water which can be abstracted from groundwater is governed by the empirical equation of \cite{}, expressed

\begin{equation}
  Q = \frac{t \times 129574.1 \times BHP}{d + ((255.5998 \times BHP^2) / (d^2 \times D^4))}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Q$ is well discharge in litres, $t$ is the duration of the irrigation event in hours, $BHP$ is the horsepower of the pump, $d$ is the average depth of the well in metres, and $D$ is the diameter of the suction pipe in inches. In cases where farmers possess more than one well, the average horsepower of the pumps is used in the above equation and the resulting well discharge multiplied by the number of wells.\\

The daily irrigation demand deficit is computed by subtracting the irrigation supply from the irrigation demand. This is accumulated during the growing season and used in the farm economics module to inform decisions about potential investments. \\

