\subsection{Farm economics}

\subsubsection{Capital}
We use farmer capital as an indicator of the socio-economic wellbeing of the agricultural population within the study area. The change in capital of a smallholder is expressed by \citet{pande_sociohydrological_2016} as a function of capital depreciation, income and expenditure, and loans received. It is expressed as

\begin{equation}
  \frac{dK}{dT}(T) = -\delta \frac{K(T)}{\Delta T} + m(T) - z(T) + w(t)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\frac{dK}{dT}(T)$ is the change in capital $K$ during year $T$, $m(T)$ and $z(T)$ (Rs/year) are respectively the income and expenditure of the smallholder in year $T$, and $w(T)$ is the value of the loan taken in year $T$. \\

Each farmer is assigned a current account, from which operational expenses are made, and a savings account which is used for making long-term investments. The savings account is updated at the end of the agricultural year if the current account has a positive balance. If at any point during the year the current account balance becomes negative, money stored in the savings account may be used to meet the shortfall. In the event that savings cannot meet the shortfall, farmers may take out a government loan. This option is available to the farmer up to a maximum level of debt.

\subsubsection{Income}
We consider the sale of crops to be the principal component of smallholder income. It is calculated as follows:

\begin{equation}
m_{a}(T) = \sum\limits_{c=1}^{n_{c}} y(T) q(T) A(T)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $m_{a}(T)$ (Rs/year) is income from crop sales in year $T$, $n_{c}$ is the number of crops grown in an agricultural year and $y(T)$, $q(T)$ and $A(T)$ are the yield, price and area of crop $c$.\\

% In addition to crop sales we consider interest on savings, $m_{s}$.\\

Income depends on farm area. Change in farm area over time is the result of many complex and interacting factors including population growth, urbanisation, cultural factors including how the land is divided to the next generation, and farm income and access to resources. Given a lack of information about these factors, we choose not to include farm area as an endogenous variable. Instead, we use land holding data from India's agricultural census, which shows the number of farms belonging to five size classes (0-1 Ha, 1-2 Ha, 2-4 Ha, 4-6 Ha) to upscale farm level output to the grid cell.

\subsubsection{Expenditure}
Smallholders incur a variety of expenses during the year \citep{}, which include the cost of agricultural production, $z_{a}(T) (Rs/year)$ and costs associated with running a household, $z_{x}(T)$ (Rs/year). The total expenditure may therefore be expressed as

\begin{equation}
  z(T) = z_{a}(T) + z_{x}(T).
\end{equation}

\noindent Expenses related to agricultural production include interest on debt, $z_{w}(T)$ (Rs/year), purchase of seeds, $z_{s}(T)$ (Rs/year), running costs of groundwater pumps, $z_{d}(T)$ (Rs/year), maintenance costs associated with tubewells and pumpsets, and purchase of fertiliser $z_{f}(T)$ (Rs/year):

\begin{equation}
  z_{a}(T) = z_{w}(T) + z_{s}(T) + z_{d}(T) + z_{m}(T) + z_{f}(T)
\end{equation}

\noindent We estimate the running cost of a tubewell pump as

\begin{equation}
  z_{d} = \sum\limits_{t=1}^{365} v_{d}(t,T) \times I_{g}(t,T) \times q_{d}(T)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $q_{d}(T)$ (Rs/litre) is the unit price of diesel and $v_{d}(t,T)$ (litres) is the volume of diesel required to pump a unit volume of water from depth $h$ (m). We calculate $v_{d}(t,T)$ using the empirical relationship set out in \citet{}, as follows:

\begin{equation}
    v_{d}(t,T) = \left(\frac{(0.1133 \times h(t,T)) + 0.7949}{102.87}\right)\eta
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\eta$ is the pump efficiency. 

