\subsection{Model domain and scope}
Figure~X shows the spatial extent and key physical features of the study area. The model region extends beyond the surface catchment boundary in order to utilise physically realistic boundaries for the hydrogeological system. These boundaries consist of the Ganges river to the south, the X and Y rivers to the east and west, respectively, and the Himalaya to the north. The temporal extent of the model is between 1970 and 2010, which covers most of the operational period of the Gandak barrage and canal system, which became operational in 1968. The model has a spatial resolution of 5 arcminutes $\times$ 5 arcminutes and has a daily time step. Each grid cell is initialised with \textit{n} farmers, with \textit{n} assumed to be large enough to adequately capture the variability in farm characteristics and range of potential farmer decisions. 

The barrage, which controls the provision of water to the river system and irrigation canals, is the upper boundary condition to our conceptual model. The barrage operation is governed by an operating manual... and does not currently include any allocation for environmental flows \citep{}. The canal network is known to be mostly unlined, with leakage rates estimated to be around X\% \citep{}. Given the volume of water carried by the canal network, which is in the order of Y (use monthly quota to estimate), this would translate to annual recharge of between A-B mm when averaged across the entire basin downstream of the barrage. Thus, canal leakage is an important process to include in the model. It is also likely that recharge from the canal system plays an important role in river baseflow, which is important to the river ecology \citep{}. 

