\subsection{Climate forcing data}
We use Indian Meteorological Deparartment (IMD) daily gridded precipitation data at 0.25 degree resolution \citep{}. For the section of the study area located in Nepal, we used precipitation data from the Princeton global meteorological forcing dataset \citep{sheffield_development_2006}. We estimated reference evapotranspiration using the Penman-Monteith equation \citep{}, with input variables from the Princeton dataset.

\subsection{Parameter specification}

\subsubsection{Soil parameters}
We retrieved the required soil parameters from HiHydroSoil \citep{}; a composite dataset of soil hydraulic properties derived from global and regional soil information. Specifically, we retrieved values of the resisdual water content, the water content at field capacity, wilting point and saturation point at the native resolution of 30 arcseconds and aggregated to the model resolution. All variables were retrieved for two soil layers.

\subsubsection{Surface-water routing parameters}
We derived operational rules for the Gandak barrage from the monthly releases specified in the original agreement between India and Nepal \citep{}. We assume the storage pond immediately upstream of the barrage is steady-state; hence we assume that discharge immediately upstream of the barrage must be divided between the east and west canal branches and the main river downstream of the barrage. [Further explanation from Chris Jackson].

\subsubsection{Groundwater parameters}
Describe groundwater parameters, including initial condition (Johanna Scheidegger)

\subsubsection{Crop parameters}
We obtained crop parameters from various sources. We used potential yield from FAO GAEZ and local agricultural inventory data. Crop calendars were compiled from data contained in the MIRCA2000 dataset \citep{portmann_???_2010}, national data \citep{moulds_???_20XX}. We used the relative length of crop growth stages (initial, development) and maximum rooting depth from the Global Crop Water Model \citep{siebert}. Lastly, we used crop coefficients for rice and wheat from \citet{}, and from GCWM for sugarcane.

% Table showing crop parameters

\subsubsection{Farm parameters}
We set the number of representative farms in each grid cell to 100; a figure which balances our interest in representing as much as possible the socioeconomic hetereogeneity between farms with the required computational effort. The representative farms were divided into categories representing land holding size intervals. Five farm size categories were considered, representing farm sizes between 0-1 Ha, 1-2 Ha, 2-4 Ha, 4-6Ha and 6Ha and above, which correspond with those used in India's agricultural census, allowing us to straightforwardly upscale to the grid level variables which are computed at the farm level. The size of individual farms was randomly selected within the respective farm size intervals, weighted such that the average area of farms across all cells belonging to the given district equalled (approximately) the average area given in the agricultural census data for 1970-71. At each time point during the simulation we prescibe the proportion of agricultural land belonging to each farm size category, using data derived from India's agricultural census.

It would be prohibitively computationally expensive to explicitly model every farmer in a grid cell. Instead, we parameterise 100 representative farmers, equally divided between the five size categories specified above. To upscale farm-level variables to the grid level we introduce a scaling factor, $sf_{ij}$:

\begin{equation}
  sf_{i,j} = \frac{A_{ij}}{\sum\limits_{k=1}^{n} A_{ijk}}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $A_{ij}$ is the area of cropland in grid cell $i$ belonging to farm size category $j$, $A_{ijk}$ is the area of farm $k$ and $n(=20)$ is the total number of farms in category $j$.

