\section{Discussion}
Return to the questions driving the research. What do the results show? \\

Hydrological models are associated with a large amount of epistemic uncertainty arising from a lack of knowledge about the appropriate mathematical representation of hydrological processes at different spatial scales, a lack of knowledge about the physical properties and boundary conditions of catchments and a lack of knowledge about the reliability of input and validation datasets \citep{beven_changing_1989}. [...] The various models accumulated by the hydrological modelling community may be viewed as working hypotheses about the hydrological behaviour of a place (refs). Integrated models... Perhaps unsurprisingly, modelling has emerged as one of the primary methods of inquiry in socio-hydrological research \citep{}. The model we have described attempts to advance socio-hydrological modelling by adapting a farm-scale model to a spatially-explicit modelling framework in which the hydrological boundary conditions are provided by a coupled model framework. In addition, the model is an attempt to apply the principles of socio-hydrology in a region where both hydrological and socioeconomic data is scarce, but where there is a clear need for improved understanding of the relationship between human and natural systems. As a result of this data scarcity the model contains some important shortcomings. \\

The model is not intended as a predictive tool; rather, it is intended to explore spatial patterns which arise from heterogeneity in the quantity and source of water for irrigation. \\

The model was developed from field data presented in \citet{okeeffe_???_2016} and \citet{okeeffe_???_2018}. Mention number of data points in comparison to the number of farmers. Also talk about the uncertainty. \\

Put in context of Murrumbidgee, pendulum swing. \\

The presented model presents an approach to include human behaviour in earth system models, advocated by \citet{nazemi_???_2015}. Together with space and time dimensions, we add a cross-cutting human dimension within which we can explore the effects of diverse human behaviour on water resources, and vice versa. We have focused on human activities related to agricultural water management. There is a need to develop a consistent approach to modelling human activities in earth system models which is applicable in various sectors. Considering data availability, process understanding and computational resources, this is a challenging task. Our intent is that this modelling framework contributes to this ultimate goal.

The coupled model of the Gandak basin reveals several knowledge gaps. Many of these concern the physical system. The availability of river and canal discharge data in northern India is poor. Soil properties are derived from global datasets associated with a large amount of uncertainty \citep{}. Aside from uncertainty about the physical system, there are large gaps in understanding of smallholder systems. We have taken a water-centred approach, because fieldwork and reviews of the literature showed that this is an important variable. However, there are myriad other factors which influence farmer behaviour. Soil salinity is an important factor across the basin. To develop better models there is a need to identify the strengths and weaknesses of current models and highlight the processes and systems that are poorly understood in order to drive the collection of new or more accurate data and devise field studies of specific processes (refs). This is one of the main aims of uncertainty analysis (refs) and fundamental to the notion of modelling as a learning process. A lack of discourse between modellers and and field experimentalists means that that the current generation of hydrological models do not always reflect the advances in process understanding gained from field studies \citep{mcdonnell_moving_2007,clark_framework_2008}. \\

Necessarily, the model presented here is a simplification of the actual system. For example, we have not considered the effect of irrigation practices on soil quality; an issue which is increasingly important in many parts of the Indo-Gangetic Plain and which has a dramatic effect on viability of farmland. Although we have considered population growth and demographic change as boundary conditions to the system, in reality these processes are intertwined with agricultural wellbeing and farm profitability. Running the model in historical mode has to some extent allowed us to ignore these complexities and use observed data to constrain the model. However, ultimately our intention is to run the model in predictive mode, for which it will be necessary to include some of these processes as endogenous. A basic assumption of the farmer behaviour module is that humans (farmers) will act rationally on the available information in order to promote their wellbeing. This is consistent with several other socio-hydrological models \citep[e.g.][]{}. % \citep{pande_progress_2018}. \\

Selection of endogenous and exogenous processes. Food production in the Indo-Gangetic Plain is intrinsically linked to the national and global economy. According to \citet{pande_progress_2017}, ``in the context of socio-hydrology, a system is open if there are fluxes that flow across system boundaries''. ``Local water resources are used to produce commodities that are consumed in distant places (Konar et al. 2011)'' \citep{srinivasan_prediction_2016}. Currently, therefore, we treat farm size as an exogenous variable to the model. Clearly, farm size is intrinsically linked to the socioeconomic system.\\

Highlight importance of primary data collection which is specific to the catchment under consideration. Emphasise the role of models as a conceptual representation of a system, and the need for continual dialogue between field work and model development. Compare the use of 'toy' models vs. models which actually generate insight about a specific place. The process of building the model has provided insight into the sort of data required to build spatially-explicit models which incorporate social processes, and highlighted gaps in current data. Some of these have started to be addressed in recent years. For example, there has been a new focus on land system maps. The IIASA-IFPRI cropland map was accompanied by a map of estimated field size, which is known to correlate with socioeconomic variables such as the degree of mechanization (refs). \\

It is tempting to seek to apply the modelling framework at ever-larger spatial extents. We caution against this, for various reasons. Although there has been some progress, there is a lack of unifying theories of human behaviour, or even an understanding of the full range of human behaviour with respect to agricultural water use. The development of the model has been informed by a number of farmer interviews and focus groups \citep{okeeffe}, as well as knowledge of the study region built up over several years \citep{atree}. Model-Data-Model paradigm is essential in modelling efforts which seek to include human processes. Moreover, we have much to learn from sociological research methods. \\

